==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|playen|lang=enm}}, {{term|pleyen|lang=enm}}, {{term|pleȝen|lang=enm}}, {{term|plæien|lang=enm}}, also {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|plaȝen|lang=enm}}, {{term|plawen|lang=enm}} {{gloss|> English {{term|plaw|lang=en}}}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|pleġan}}, {{term/t|ang|pleoġan}}, {{term/t|ang|plæġan}}, and {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|pleġian}}, {{term/t|ang|pleaġian}}, {{term|plagian||to play, move about sportively, frolic, dance; move rapidly; divert or amuse oneself, occupy or busy oneself; play a game, sport with, exercise, exercise one’s self in any way for the sake of amusement; play with; play with a person, toy; strive after; play on an instrument; contend, fight; clap the hands, applaud; make sport of, mock; cohabit (with)|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*pleganą}}, {{term/t|gem-pro|*plehaną||to care about, be concerned with}} and {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*plegōną||to engage, move}}; both perhaps from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*blek-||to move, move about}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bal-}} (compare Ancient Greek {{term/t|grc|βλύω}}, {{term/t|grc|βλύζω||I gush out, spring}}, Sanskrit {{term/t|sa|बल्बलीति||it whirls, twirls|tr=balbalīti}}). Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|play||to act or move briskly, cause to move, stir|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|plegia||to look after, care for, maintain|lang=stq}}, West Frisian {{term|pleegje|lang=fy}}, {{term|pliigje||to commit, perform, bedrive|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|dum|-}} {{term|pleyen|lang=dum}} {{gloss|"to dance, leap for joy, rejoice, be glad"; > Modern {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|pleien||to play a particular children's game|lang=nl}}}}, Dutch {{term|plegen||to commit, bedrive, practice|lang=nl}}, German {{term|pflegen||to care for, be concerned with, attend to, tend|lang=de}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|pleie||to tend to, nurse|lang=da}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|pläga||to be wont to, be accustomed to|lang=sv}}. Related also to {{etyl|ang|